  "prompt": "Cost for 1kg of A is 260 USD and 1kg of B is 380. AB is made by mixing A and B. If 1kg of AB costs 300, what was the ratio that A and B has mixed?",
  "response": "To find the ratio in which A and B were mixed to create AB with a cost of $300 per kg, we can use the following steps:\n\n1. **Define Variables:**\n   Let \\( x \\) be the amount (in kg) of A used in the mixture.\n   Let \\( y \\) be the amount (in kg) of B used in the mixture.\n\n2. **Set Up Equations:**\n   The total weight of the mixture is \\( x + y \\) kg.\n   The total cost of the mixture is \\( 260x + 380y \\) dollars.\n   The cost per kg of the mixture is given as $300.\n\n3. **Cost Per Kg Equation:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{260x + 380y}{x + y} = 300\n   \\]\n\n4. **Solve the Equation:**\n   Multiply both sides by \\( x + y \\) to clear the denominator:\n   \\[\n   260x + 380y = 300(x + y)\n   \\]\n   Expand and simplify:\n   \\[\n   260x + 380y = 300x + 300y\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   380y - 300y = 300x - 260x\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   80y = 40x\n   \\]\n   Divide both sides by 40:\n   \\[\n   2y = x\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   \\frac{x}{y} = \\frac{2}{1}\n   \\]\n\n5. **Conclusion:**\n   The ratio of A to B in the mixture is \\( 2:1 \\).",
